This paper deals with wireless object tracking applications and the design of a protocol for maximizing throughput among a set of heterogeneous broadcasting nodes with differing power consumption levels, each subject to a strict ultra-low-power budget. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of Lagrangian methods, which are commonly used in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also deals with the optimization of a system subject to constraints, which is a common theme in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper involves the use of information theory and optimization techniques, which are commonly used in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the evaluation of the protocol's performance through simulations and experiments, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
